    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin misstep! Let me clarify the legal side of things without the goblin antics. The third party holding the money in an escrow account is typically a neutral entity, such as a title company or an escrow agent. Their role is to act as a trustworthy guardian of your funds, ensuring that the money is only released when all the agreed-upon conditions of the real estate transaction are met. This includes things like the buyer securing financing, the seller completing necessary repairs, and the house passing inspections. \n\nTo ensure that they won't lose your money, these third parties are regulated by various laws and must adhere to strict professional standards. They are required to keep your funds in a separate, secure account, and they must follow the instructions you provide in the escrow agreement. Additionally, they are often bonded, which means they have insurance to cover any potential losses. This way, you can rest assured that your treasure is in safe hands, and the only goblins you'll encounter are the ones in the fairy tales, not in your real estate transaction.",
