      "content": "Absolutely, if there's a problem with the house inspection, the money typically remains in the escrow account until the issue is resolved. The escrow agent will work with both you and the seller to determine the best course of action. This might involve negotiating a repair plan, adjusting the sale price, or even canceling the deal if the problem is too significant.\n\nThe agent, or the escrow agent, will release the funds to the seller once all the conditions of the escrow agreement have been met. This includes:\n\n1. The buyer securing financing and providing proof of funds.\n2. The seller completing any agreed-upon repairs or fixes.\n3. The house passing all inspections and any other agreed-upon conditions.\n\nOnce these conditions are satisfied, the escrow agent will release the funds to the seller, typically through a wire transfer or check. The agent will also provide you with a final statement detailing the release of funds and any other relevant information about the transaction. So, in essence, the escrow agent acts as a referee, ensuring that both parties play by the rules and that the game is fair for everyone involved. No goblins here, just a fair and orderly process to ensure a smooth transition to your new home.",
